    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>Plaza de la Virgen is the main historic square of Valencia's old city, located at the heart of the Ciutat Vella. The square is bounded on the east by Valencia Cathedral (La Seu), on the north by the Basilica de Nuestra Señora de los Desamparados, and at its centre stands the Turia Fountain — a Baroque sculpture depicting the River Turia with eight female allegorical figures representing its tributaries.</p>
    <p>The plaza has served as a civic and religious gathering point since Roman times, when it formed part of the forum of the Roman colony of Valentia, founded in 138 BC. The current configuration of the square reflects centuries of urban layering: the Cathedral was built between the 13th and 15th centuries on the site of a former mosque, while the Baroque Basilica dates from 1667. Every Thursday at noon, the Water Tribunal (Tribunal de las Aguas) convenes publicly on the Cathedral steps — the world's oldest functioning court, inscribed as a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage in 2009.</p>
    <p>The plaza is pedestrianised and freely accessible at all times. It connects directly to Plaza de la Reina to the south and to the narrow streets of the Barrio del Carmen to the north and west. The Cathedral and Basilica have separate admission fees and their own official websites for ticketing. Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</p>
